<div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
     <p>Would I fare better at home and succeed in having children by appeasing the gods? </p>
</div>            
<div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
<p>¿Me iría mejor en casa y conseguiría tener hijos propiciando a los dioses? </p>
</div>
            
<div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
<p>On <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱλάσκομαι</foreign> in the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#Bonnechere2018"/></bibl> and, especially, <bibl><ptr target="#Georgoudi"/> <citedRange>forthcoming </citedRange></bibl>. Owing to the lack of context, it is not possible to determine whether the verb means “to appease” or “to propitiate” the gods.</p>
                
                 <p n="Ithaca results">Ithaca attributes the inscription to Epirus with high accuracy (91.42%) and dates it to the mid-fifth century BC. Notably, the probability distribution is strongly concentrated in 450-440 BC (27.27%). As for the restoration outputs, Ithaca clearly favours the restoration <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱλασκόμενος</foreign>, while the remaining alternatives receive substantially lower confidence scores. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline7B_2026_06_24.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline7B.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline7B_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
